explanation:
For deciding whether any portion of OS_CondVarCreate is statically unreachable you must examine all macros/functions that can alter control flow or determine branch outcomes and the table/record types the macros manipulate. Rationale for each symbol:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER: macro at function start — may return, set an error, or abort; directly affects reachability of the rest of the function.
- OS_CHECK_APINAME: same as above for var_name; can early-exit or alter control flow.
- OS_ObjectIdAllocateNew: produces return_code used in the if(return_code == OS_SUCCESS) branch; its implementation determines whether the then-block can ever be reached.
- OS_SUCCESS: value compared to return_code — needed to evaluate the conditional semantics.
- OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_CONDVAR: constant passed to OS_ObjectIdAllocateNew; may affect allocation behavior/return values.
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: macro used to get condvar pointer from token — may contain calls/expressions that affect flow or can be a no-op; needed to see side effects and any internal calls (e.g., to index/global helpers).
- OS_OBJECT_INIT: macro used to initialize the table entry/name — may modify data or contain control-flow constructs (e.g., checks/returns); required to know whether subsequent code is reachable.
- OS_condvar_table: the global table referenced by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; its existence/definition and indexing semantics determine whether that expression is valid/reachable.
- OS_condvar_internal_record_t: type of condvar entries; needed to know fields (like obj_name) that OS_OBJECT_INIT manipulates and whether those accesses are valid.
- OS_object_token_t: type of token variable used by allocation and later macros — its representation may affect macro expansions and control flow.
- osal_id_t: type of the out parameter var_id — needed if macros read/modify it (e.g., in finalize) and to understand side effects.
- OS_CondVarCreate_Impl: called inside the then-block — may not return or may change control flow (longjmp/abort); needed to decide reachability of subsequent statements.
- OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew: called to finalize and may perform notification/cleanup and alter return path; its behavior affects whether following code is reachable and how the function returns.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: appears in static call graph and is commonly used by object-table macros — include to inspect any index-based checks/side-effects used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET or OS_OBJECT_INIT.
- OS_ObjectIdGlobalFromToken: likewise used by macros to convert token to global pointer/base; may affect control flow or validity of accesses.
- OS_printf: present in the static call graph (likely used inside macros or callees) and can be part of error paths or diagnostic code that affects reachability (e.g., prints then aborts in debug builds).
- UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr: these unit-test stub helpers appear in the static graph for this function (macros or instrumented builds). They can modify behavior (return values, aborts) or inject early returns in test configurations; include them to determine whether any code is only reachable in test vs production builds.

Analyze these symbols (macro definitions and function implementations/types/constants) to determine whether any portion of the if-block or following statements can never be executed in any build/configuration; that determines violation of the MISRA unreachable-code rule.
